   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Python Tutorials\n",
    "\n",
    "These tutorials are written in Jupyter, but you can also run them in `ipython` if you prefer. For Jupyter, we need to set the options below, but if you are running only `ipython`, instead of `%matplotlib inline` try using `%matplotlib qt5` or `%matplotlib osx`, depending on your system.\n",
    "\n",
    "You should start Python in the directory where you have the IRIS-9 data (e.g. `~/iris9/` as we defined earlier)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import astropy.io.fits as fits\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from astropy.wcs import WCS\n",
    "# Set up some default matplotlib options\n",
    "plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [10, 6]\n",
    "plt.rcParams['xtick.direction'] = 'out'\n",
    "plt.rcParams['image.origin'] = 'lower'\n",
    "plt.rcParams['image.cmap'] = 'viridis'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Mg II Dopplergrams\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial we are going to produce a Dopplergram for the Mg II k line from an IRIS 400-step raster. The Dopplergram is obtained by subtracting the intensities at symmetrical velocity shifts from the line core (e.g. ±50 km/s). For this kind of analysis we need a consistent wavelength calibration for each step of the raster.\n",
    "\n",
    "This very large dense raster took more than three hours to complete the 400 scans (30 s exposures), which means that the spacecraft's orbital velocity changes during the observations. This means that any precise wavelength calibration will need to correct for those shifts.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's open the file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "iris_file = fits.open(\"iris_l2_20140708_114109_3824262996_raster_t000_r00000.fits\",\n",
    "                 memmap=True, do_not_scale_image_data=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we use `memmap` to save memory.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can now print out the spectral windows in the file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Window. Name      : wave start - wave end\n",
      "\n",
      "1. C II 1336      : 1332.70 - 1337.58 Å\n",
      "2. Fe XII 1349    : 1347.68 - 1350.90 Å\n",
      "3. O I 1356       : 1352.25 - 1356.69 Å\n",
      "4. Si IV 1394     : 1390.90 - 1396.19 Å\n",
      "5. Si IV 1403     : 1398.63 - 1406.34 Å\n",
      "6. 2832           : 2831.23 - 2834.26 Å\n",
      "7. 2814           : 2812.54 - 2816.41 Å\n",
      "8. Mg II k 2796   : 2792.98 - 2806.63 Å\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "hd = iris_file[0].header\n",
    "print('Window. Name      : wave start - wave end\\n')\n",
    "for i in range(hd['NWIN']):\n",
    "    win = str(i + 1)\n",
    "    print('{0}. {1:15}: {2:.2f} - {3:.2f} Å'\n",
    "          ''.format(win, hd['TDESC' + win], hd['TWMIN' + win], hd['TWMAX' + win]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that Mg II is in window 8, so let's load those data and get the WCS information to construct the wavelength arrays and get coordinates:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data = iris_file[8].data\n",
    "wcs = WCS(iris_file[8].header)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And let's calculate the wavelength array:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "m_to_nm = 1e9  # convert wavelength to nm\n",
    "wave = wcs.all_pix2world(np.arange(wcs._naxis[0]), [0.], [0.], 1)[0] * m_to_nm"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see how the the spatially averaged spectrum looks like:"
   ]

    "aux = iris_file[-2]\n",
    "v_obs = aux.data[:, aux.header['OBS_VRIX']]\n",
    "v_obs /= 1000.  # convert to km/s\n",
    "plt.plot(v_obs)\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Orbital velocity (km/s)\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Scan number\")"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To look at intensities at any given scan we only need to subtract this velocity shift from the wavelength scale, but to look at the whole image at a given wavelength we must interpolate the original data to take this shift into account. Here is a way to do it (note that array dimensions apply to this specific set only!):"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.constants import c\n",
    "from scipy.interpolate import interp1d\n",
    "c_kms = c / 1000.\n",
    "wave_shift = - v_obs * wave[350] / (c_kms)\n",
    "# linear interpolation in wavelength, for each scan\n",
    "for i in range(iris_file[0].header['NRASTERP']):\n",
    "    tmp = interp1d(wave - wave_shift[i], data[i], bounds_error=False)\n",
    "    data[i] = tmp(wave)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And now we can plot the shifted data to see that the large scale shifts have disappeared:"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Some residual shift remains, but we will not correct for it here. A more elaborate correction can be obtained by the IDL routine `iris_prep_wavecorr_l2`, but this has not yet been ported to Python see the [IDL version of this tutorial]( http://iris.lmsal.com/itn26/tutorials.html#mg-ii-dopplergrams) for more details.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can use the calibrated data for example to calculate Dopplergrams. A Dopplergram is here defined as the difference between the intensities at two wavelength positions at the same (and opposite) distance from the line core. For example, at +/- 50 km/s from the Mg II k3 core. To do this, let us first calculate a velocity scale for the k line and find the indices of the -50 and +50 km/s velocity positions (here using the convention of negative velocities for up flows): "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mg_k_centre = 279.63521  # in nm\n",
    "pos = 50  # in km/s around line centre\n",
    "velocity =  (wave - mg_k_centre) * c_kms / mg_k_centre\n",
    "index_p = np.argmin(np.abs(velocity - pos))\n",
    "index_m = np.argmin(np.abs(velocity + pos))\n",
    "doppl = data[..., index_m] - data[..., index_p]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And now we can plot this as before (intensity units are again arbitrary because of the unscaled DNs):"

   "source": [
    "## Flare 4-step raster: SJI and spectrograph"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This exercise will be solved mostly by the participants. The [low-level guide to IRIS with Python](https://folk.uio.no/tiago/teaching/ipylow) will serve as a reference for most of the tasks necessary to complete this exercise.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this exercise we will combine the slit-jaw and spectrograph images taken during a small flare. The data are from 2014-11-07, with file names `iris_l2_20141107_160734_3860258971_*`. The programme was a 4-step raster, and there are 80 repeats. In the files provided there is only the 2796 slit-jaw.\n",
    "\n",
    "Start by loading the slit-jaw file and then do the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "* Find out what is the timestep at `2014-11-07T16:19:07.800`. Remember that just like in the raster files, the array with times is saved in the second to last extension of the SJI fits files. Plot the SJI image at that timestep, in solar (x, y) coordinates in arcsec.\n",
    "* Did the exposure time vary for this slit-jaw file? Ie, was the Auto Exposure Compensation (AEC) triggered? Check the second to last extension in the file, the data column number for exposure times is saved in the keyword `EXPTIMES` in the second to last extension.\n",
    "* Check what is the closest raster file for the time of `2014-11-07T16:19:07.800`. Load that file, and check the spectra for the window `Si IV 1403`. Was the exposure saturated at any position? \n",
    "* Get the solar y coordinates (in arcsec) of the slit using the WCS information in the header of the loaded raster file. Hint 1: this can be obtained in a similar way as we obtain the wavelength from the WCS header, but for the y coordinate we need to get the second WCS coordinate, e.g.: `y = wcs.all_pix2world([0.], np.arange(N_PIX_SLIT), [0.], 0)[1]`. Hint 2: note that astropy's WCS internally uses degrees as unit for the radial coordinates. If you just print the wcs object, you will see that in this case that `CRVAL[2] = -0.1672825` (in degrees), which is about -10' (you can also check this in the SJI plot). \n",
    "* You can now put everything together and make an image plot (`imshow`) of the `Si IV 1403`, using the solar y scale on the y axis and the wavelength scale on the x axis, for any of the raster positions. To do this you supply the keyword argument `extent` to `imshow`, e.g.: `extent=[wavelength.min(), wavelength.max(), y.min(), y.max()]`. The results should be something like:\n",
    "\n",
    "![Si IV 1403](images/SiIV1403.png \"Si IV 1403\")"
   ]
